lds don’t include it. I’m thinking adding it could improve my meaningful auto-config tests. Should I include test utilities in this deterministic setup?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Addressing auto-configuration challenges**\\n\\nHandling conditions and auto-configuration feels a bit cumbersome. I've noticed that the upstream module tests use `testImplementation(project(\\\":core:spring-boot-test\\\"))` and utilize the ApplicationContextRunner, which seems like a solid approach. It gives me concrete evidence of what needs to be included for effective testing. I wonder if I should follow that same pattern to streamline my process and avoid potential pitfalls in my own implementation. It’s important to keep things clear and manageable!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_i8ROhENDJwuaOo5fdcGbj0VO|fc_0c0414957c32668b016a3ef95b07a0819387c3e974706ab491", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport urllib.request\nfor a in ['spring-boot-micrometer-metrics','spring-boot-reactor-netty','spring-boot-tomcat','spring-boot-test']:\n url=f'https://repo.maven.apache.org/maven2/org/springframework/boot/{a}/4.1.0-RC1/{a}-4.1.0-RC1.pom'\n try:\n  data=urllib.request.urlopen(url, timeout=10).read().decode()\n  print(a, 'OK')\n except Exception as e: print(a, e)\nPY", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 982, "output": 1453, "cacheRead": 50688, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 53123, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782511944967, "responseId": "resp_0c0414957c32668b016a3ef949d76481939ebcb7a631bfe61f"}}
